# ====================================================================
# M0 (minimal assembler) for riscv64 UEFI -- DEFINE / strings / imms
# ====================================================================
#
# Role in the bootstrap chain:
#   M0 reads .M1 source (the next-richer-than-hex2 layer in the
#   stage0 toolchain), expands DEFINE macros, converts ASCII string
#   literals into hex byte streams, and encodes RISC-V immediate
#   forms into hex2-friendly tokens. Output is a .hex2 file that
#   hex2.efi can link.
#
# Pipeline (every pass walks the same singly-linked token list):
#   1. Tokenize_Line     -- split input on whitespace + strings,
#                           build LL_TOKEN { NEXT, TYPE, TEXT,
#                           EXPRESSION } entries
#   2. Reverse_List      -- tokens were prepended for O(1) build,
#                           reverse to natural source order
#   3. Identify_Macros   -- mark DEFINE tokens as TYPE=MACRO,
#                           remember their key/value pair
#   4. Line_Macro        -- substitute macro key occurrences with
#                           their value (one-pass; no nested macros)
#   5. Process_String    -- expand "..." literals into hex byte
#                           tokens (handles standard escapes)
#   6. Eval_Immediates   -- detect RV64 immediate forms (e.g.
#                           !value, %hi, %lo, S-imm splits) and
#                           rewrite as the bytes that hex2 expects
#   7. Preserve_Other    -- pass through label defs/refs unchanged
#   8. Print_Hex         -- walk the list, emit each token's TEXT
#
# Memory layout (allocated up front via boot->allocate_pool):
#   - 8 MiB stack switch (we leave UEFI's small stack to allow
#     deep recursion in Eval_Immediates)
#   - 64 MiB working pool (covers cc_riscv64.M1 worst-case
#     allocations: tokens + scratch + immediate-expansion tables)
#   - 4 MiB file buffer (cc_riscv64.M1 is ~5000 lines but compresses
#     under 4 MB after preprocessing)
#   - 4 KiB scratch (token text scratch buffer, rezeroed often)
#
# Debug 'dbg X' tracing:
#   dbg_char prints a single ASCII byte to ConOut and is sprinkled
#   between phases (A=Allocate, B=Buffer ready, T/R/I/L/S/E/P/H/Z
#   for the pipeline phases). Lets us pinpoint where the assembler
#   hangs without an interactive debugger.
#
# Stack switch quirk:
#   UEFI's default stack is 16-128 KiB depending on firmware. We
#   immediately allocate an 8 MiB pool and switch sp into it
#   (saving original sp in s0) so that deep recursion doesn't
#   crash. We restore the original sp before returning.
#
# Generated by gen-M0-rv64.py.
# Total: 4352 bytes, code: 3713 bytes.
#
# Calling convention:
#   s0 = saved UEFI sp (for clean exit after stack switch)
#   s1 = malloc bump pointer (advances; never freed individually)
#   s2 = fin / buf_pos (input file -> in-memory buffer position)
#   s3 = fout, s4 = HEAD (token list), s5 = file_buffer / buf_end
#   s6 = scratch (4 KiB scratch buffer base)
#   s7 = ImageHandle, s8 = boot_services
#   s9 = rootdir, s10 = root_device, s11 = pool_start (for FreePool)

